 great and influential cultures that, in fact, had virtually no contact during the ancient period. The patterns of thought and the cultural productions of early China and ancient Greece represent two significantly different responses to the myriad problems that human beings confront. Throughout this volume the comparisons between these cultures evince two critical ideas. First, that thinking is itself an inherently comparative activity. Through making comparisons, the familiar becomes strange, and the strange somewhat more familiar. Second, since we think through comparisons, we should think them all the way through. How valid and productive are the comparisons and contrasts made between particular works and different styles of thought that emerged from two different, although contemporaneous, cultural contexts?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aRites and ceremonieszChina. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurrant, Stephen W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurrant, Stephen W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeightley, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNylan, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlaks, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPuett, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaphals, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaussy, Haun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaberg, David, e